SIMPLE: casemate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Casemate
<hw>Case"mate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>casemate</ets>, fr. It. <ets>casamatta</ets>, prob. from <ets>casa</ets> house + <ets>matto</ets>, f. <ets>matta</ets>, mad, weak, feeble, dim. from the same source as E. <ets>-mate</ets> in <ets>checkmate</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>A bombproof chamber, usually of masonry, in which cannon may be placed, to be fired through embrasures; or one capable of being used as a magazine, or for quartering troops.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A hollow molding, chiefly in cornices.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Casemated</ent>⟦br⟧
